<h2>About Vaccination Passports</h2>
<p class="padding" style="text-align: left">“Texas Gov. Abbott signed an executive order on Friday, banning COVID-19
    vaccine and mask mandates in Texas, despite cases continuing to rise in the state.” <a
            href="https://www.businessinsider.com/gov-abbott-banned-covid-19-vaccine-mask-mandates-in-texas-2021-7">(source)</a>
    “It’s beyond bizarre. It’s
    shameful,” <a
            href="https://www.wfla.com/community/health/coronavirus/its-beyond-bizarre-norwegian-cruise-ceo-blasts-floridas-appeal-of-vaccine-passport-ruling/">Norwegian
        Cruise Line CEO Frank Del Rio remarked</a> at Florida Governor Ron DeSantis for banning
    COVID-19
    vaccine passports. Even before the current pandemic, such passports <a
            href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4775877/">already exist</a> for proof of vaccination
    or
    prophylaxis. The World Health Organization (WHO) and International Health Regulations (IHRs) use yellow
    booklets
    called International Certificate of Vaccination of Prophylaxis (ICVP). The health agency responsible for
    vaccination
    or prophylaxis enter important data, such as hospitalization or vaccination date, vaccination manufacturer,
    and a
    seal of authenticity to validate such medical history. Currently, select countries <a
            href="https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/yellowbook/2020/preparing-international-travelers/yellow-fever-vaccine-and-malaria-prophylaxis-information-by-country">require
        ICVPs for proof
        of
        vaccination against yellow fever</a>, such as Brazil and Senegal. Despite the ICVP’s existence since 2005, no
    developments have been made for long-term support, facilitating discussion for a potential digital version.
    <a
            href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4775877/">facilitating discussion for a potential digital
        version.</a>
    Although proof of COVID-19 vaccination is still mostly paper-based, native and web-based applications that
    digitize
    vaccinations, tests, and previous infections are a necessary step forward towards efficiency, outweighing
    legal,
    ethical, and equity concerns.</p>
